 Thank you for your patience and understanding.\n\nBest\,\nSarah\n\nOn Su
 n\, Apr 5\, 2026 at 3:32 PM Gaurav Malhotra <gaurav.malhotra@goaco.com<m
 ailto:gaurav.malhotra@goaco.com>> wrote:\nTo discuss below as part of em
 ail chain:\n\nComments in Yellow made by Gaurav.\n\n====================
 ===================\n\nThanks for sharing the delivery plan — really app
 reciate the detail your team has put into it. We've had a good look thro
 ugh and wanted to raise a few things before we push forward.\n\n1. MoSCo
 W Prioritization\nWe'd like to move a few items up to "Must Have" for th
 e initial build:\n\n- Milestone notifications (payment confirmed\, kit s
 ent\, DNA received\, audio ready)\n- Offline downloads\n- Ensure that if
  an API request is retried\, it doesn’t create duplicate actions (like m
 ultiple charges or records)\, and errors are handled safely\n- Clinic vi
 ew of patient status and order history\n- Basic reporting (revenue\, tim
 e to audio ready\, active listeners\, support volume)\n- Tracking info a
 nd notifications\n- Discount and referral codes\n- Bundles and subscript
 ion model\n\nWe see these as core to the product from day one. Would lov
 e your team's take on what that means for scope and sequencing.\n\nMaybe
  the Clinic View could be a “Tracking page” of some sort to start with. 
  It be best for Lesley to come onboard to start drilling it down as it i
 mpacts a wider project plan.\n\n2. Estimates – Min/Max Ranges\nCurious w
 hat is driving the spread in the day ranges? Is it down to the mix of pe
 ople on the project\, or are there other dependencies at play (third-par
 ty APIs\, design sign-off\, technical unknowns)?  A clearer picture woul
 d help us plan better on our end.\n\nExactly as you said\, “other depend
 encies at play”.  Scope creeps\, user feedback/iterations that require u
 s to change a few things to get us into selling mode etc etc.\n\n\n3. RA
 ID Log\nA couple of things we'd like to get ahead of:\n\n- The HIPAA/US 
 privacy risk remains open with no mitigation yet—we are eager to agree o
 n an approach for this early.\n- Can we set a regular cadence to review 
 the RAID log together throughout delivery?\n\nFirst point for yourself a
 nd Lesley to work on.  2nd point - this is a standard process as part of
  PMO.\n\n\n4. Subscription & Bundle Model\nJust to be clear — this is a 
 must for us and not a "Could Have." We want to make sure the architectur
 e supports it from the start.\n\nOne for Lesley and how it impacts roadm
 ap.\n\n\n5. D365 & Power BI Licensing\nCan your team help us get a sense
  of what the ongoing licensing costs will look like post-implementation 
 — both for D365 (by role/volume) and Power BI? We want to factor these i
 nto our financial planning now rather than later.\n\nI done a quick chat
  gpt on it for 6 staff members\, keep note this is without the cloud hos
 ting costs\, and you’ll save on the google costs (after migration):\n\n\
 nProduct\n\n\nQty\n\n\nUnit price (USD)\n\n\nMonthly total\n\n\nAnnual t
 otal\n\n\nPurpose\n\n\nEssential / Optional\n\n\nMicrosoft 365 Business 
 Premium\n\n\n6\n\n\n$22.00/user/month\n\n\n$132.00\n\n\n$1\,584.00\n\n\n
 Full Microsoft 365 stack: desktop Office apps\, Exchange\, Teams\, Share
 Point\, OneDrive\, Intune and security features\n\n\nEssential\n\n\nPowe
 r BI Pro\n\n\n6\n\n\n$14.00/user/month\n\n\n$84.00\n\n\n$1\,008.00\n\n\n
 Lets all 6 users view and use shared Power BI content in the normal shar
